%F A060294 2/Pi = 1 - 5*(1/2)^3 + 9*((1*3)/(2*4))^3 - 13*((1*3*5)/(2*4*6))^3 ... - _Jason Earls_ [formula corrected by _Paul D. Hanna_, Mar 23 2013]
%F A060294 The preceding formula is 2/Pi = Sum_{n>=0} (-1)^n * (4*n+1) * Product_{k=1..n} (2*k-1)^3/(2*k)^3. - _Alexander R. Povolotsky_, Mar 24 2013. [See the Hardy reference. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Nov 13 2016]
%F A060294 2/Pi = Product_{n>=2} (p(n) + 2 - (p(n) mod 4))/p(n), where p(n) is the n-th prime. - _Alonso del Arte_, May 16 2012
%F A060294 2/Pi = Sum_{k>=0} ((2*k)!/(k!)^2)^3*((42*k+5)/(2^{12*k+3})) (due to Ramanujan). - _L. Edson Jeffery_, Mar 23 2013
%F A060294 Equals sinc(Pi/2). - _Peter Luschny_, Oct 04 2019
%F A060294 From _A.H.M. Smeets_, Apr 11 2020: (Start)
%F A060294 Equals Product_{i > 0} cos(Pi/2^(i+1)).
%F A060294 Equals Product_{i > 0} f_i(2)/2, where f_0(2) = 0, f_(i+1)(2) = sqrt(2+f_i(2)) for i >= 0; a formula by François Viète (16th century).
%F A060294 Note that cos(Pi/2^(i+1)) = f_i(2)/2, i >= 0. (End)
%F A060294 Equals lim_{n->infinity} (1/n) * Sum_{k=1..n} abs(sin(k * m)) for all nonzero integers m (conjectured). Works with cos also. - _Dimitri Papadopoulos_, Jul 17 2020
%F A060294 From _Amiram Eldar_, Sep 08 2020: (Start)
%F A060294 Equals Product_{k>=1} (1 - 1/(2*k)^2).
%F A060294 Equals lim_{k->oo} (2*k+1)*binomial(2*k,k)^2/2^(4*k).
%F A060294 Equals Sum_{k>=0} binomial(2*k,k)^2/((2*k+2)*2^(4*k)). (End)
%F A060294 Equals Sum_{k>=0} mu(4*k+1)/(4*k+1) (Nevanlinna, 1973). - _Amiram Eldar_, Dec 21 2020
%F A060294 Equals 1 - Sum_{n >= 1} (1/16^n) * binomial(2*n, n)^2 * 1/(2*n - 1). See Young, p. 264. - _Peter Bala_, Feb 17 2024
%F A060294 Equals binomial(0, 1/2) = binomial(0, -1/2). - _Peter Luschny_, Dec 05 2024
%F A060294 From _Peter Bala_, Dec 10 2024:(Start)
%F A060294 2/Pi =  1 - 1/(2 + 2/(1 + 6/(1 + 12/(1 + 20/(1 + ... + n*(n+1)/(1 + ...), a continued fraction representation due to Euler. See A346943.
%F A060294 Equals 1 - (1/2)*Sum_{n >= 0} A005566(n)*(-1/4)^n. (End)
